# Repo-wide line-ending policy. This Windows-authored repo expects CRLF in
# every working tree; scripts/lint.py enforces it. Without an explicit rule
# here the working-copy endings depend on each machine's `core.autocrlf`
# (Windows `true` -> CRLF, macOS/Linux `input` -> LF), so the same commit
# lints clean on one box and fails on another. `text=auto` keeps the repo
# blobs normalized to LF (clean diffs); `eol=crlf` forces CRLF on checkout
# on EVERY OS regardless of `core.autocrlf`. The more specific rules below
# come AFTER this line so they override it (last match wins per path).
* text=auto eol=crlf

# Vendored minified bundles — keep byte-identical across OS checkouts so
# SHA256 in static/vendor/VERSIONS.txt stays meaningful. Without these
# rules Git would apply its CRLF-conversion heuristic on Windows, which
# changes checksums but nothing visible in diffs.
static/vendor/*.js  -text
static/vendor/*.css -text

# Git hook shims live at .githooks/ (committed) and are activated per
# clone via `core.hooksPath` (python scripts/install_precommit.py). They
# MUST stay LF — a CRLF shebang line breaks bash on Linux / macOS — even
# though the rest of this Windows-authored repo is CRLF.
.githooks/* text eol=lf
